					<head>Kabbalah</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85018546" rend="visible">
						<summary>A collection of works in Lurianic kabbalah.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						<msItem n="0" rend="">
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Ḳovets be-ḳabalat ha-Ar"i</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">קובץ בקבלת האר"י</title>
							<locus from="1r" to="174v"/>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="2r" to="157v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Sefer ha-gilgulim</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">ספר הגלגולים</title>
							<author>
								<persName xml:lang="en" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/34704971">Vital, Ḥayyim ben Joseph, 1542-1620</persName>
								<persName xml:lang="he" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/34704971">ויטל, חיים בן יוסף</persName>
							</author>
							<note>
								<p>See <ref target="Avivi_2008" type="page">708-710</ref>, vol. 2.</p>
								<p>The volume contains 73 chapters, from chapter 36 on redacted by Nathan ben Reuven Shapira, with his comments, and additional glosses by Benyamin ha-Cohen, Moses ben Mordecai Zacuto, Jacob Zemah and others.</p>
								<p>Folio 137v-139v contain notes on metempsychosis by Moses ben Mordecai Zacuto.</p>
								<p>Folio 139v-158r contain Menahem Azariah of Fano's notes on metempsychosis under the heading ῾Inyane gilgulim, with an alphabetical index at the end.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="158r" to="162v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Peri ῾ets ḥayim</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">פרי עץ חיים </title>
							<author>
								<persName xml:lang="en" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/34704971">Vital, Ḥayyim ben Joseph, 1542-1620</persName>
								<persName xml:lang="he" key="http://viaf.org/viaf/34704971">ויטל, חיים בן יוסף</persName>
							</author>
							<note>
								<p>Contains only part four of the treatise, Sha῾ar ruaḥ ha-ḳodesh and Sha῾ar ha-nevu᾿ah (beginning on folio 161r).</p>
								<p>157r-158r: a tabulation of prophetic powers by Nathan ben Reuven Shapira.</p>
								<p>Folio 158r-161v: eight paragraphs quoted from works of Moses Cordovero.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
